        <h2 class="section-title">How Are Peptides Synthesized?</h2>
        <p class="section-text">
          Modern peptide synthesis primarily uses Solid-Phase Peptide Synthesis (SPPS), a revolutionary technique 
          developed by Bruce Merrifield in 1963, for which he received the Nobel Prize in Chemistry in 1984.
        </p>
        
        <div class="process-steps">
          <div class="step-card">
            <div class="step-number">1</div>
            <h4 class="step-title">Attach to Resin</h4>
            <p class="step-description">The first amino acid is attached to an insoluble polymer resin</p>
          </div>
          <div class="step-card">
            <div class="step-number">2</div>
            <h4 class="step-title">Deprotection</h4>
            <p class="step-description">Protective groups are removed from the amino acid</p>
          </div>
          <div class="step-card">
            <div class="step-number">3</div>
            <h4 class="step-title">Coupling</h4>
            <p class="step-description">Next amino acid is coupled to the growing chain</p>
          </div>
          <div class="step-card">
            <div class="step-number">4</div>
            <h4 class="step-title">Cleavage</h4>
            <p class="step-description">Completed peptide is cleaved from the resin and purified</p>
          </div>
        </div>
        
        <div class="highlight-box" style="margin-top: 40px;">
          <p>
            <strong>Quality Control:</strong> After synthesis, peptides undergo rigorous testing including HPLC analysis 
            for purity verification and Mass Spectrometry for molecular weight confirmation. Only peptides meeting strict 
            purity standards (typically ≥98%) are released for research use.
          </p>
        </div>
